A recent survey in urban Shanghai revealed high obesity rates among adults and children, mirroring developed countries.
Improved living standards contribute to this trend, with lack of exercise and high-fat diets as key factors.
Men are more prone to obesity, especially in the 7-12 and 60-70 age groups.
Health experts warn of associated risks like cardiovascular diseases and diabetes.
The government aims to reduce obesity levels by 2005.
Similar concerns exist globally, with Kuwait and the UAE facing rising diabetes rates linked to obesity.
Education on nutrition and lifestyle changes are crucial to combat these health issues.
